it.unipr.netsec.nemo.link

Class NetworkBuilder

  • java.lang.Object
    • it.unipr.netsec.nemo.link.NetworkBuilder

  • public class NetworkBuilder
extends java.lang.Object
    Creates IP networks with some well-known topologies.

    Simple topologies like linear, Manhattan, and n-ary tree have been implemented.

    IP addresses and routing-tables of all nodes are properly set-up. For the loopback addresses, a pre-configured private address block (IPv4) or ULA addresses (IPv6) are used.

      • linearIpNetwork

        public static Network linearIpNetwork(int n,
                                      long bit_rate,
                                      IpPrefix net_prefix)
        Creates a linear topology with n routers and n+1 links. The link addresses are automatically assigned starting from the given supernet prefix.

        No distinction is done between core and access links; all links are considered access links.

        The router addresses are assigned by giving host id 1 to the router attached to the first link, host id 1 to the router on the left of each link, host id 2 to the router on the right of each link, except for first link. Note: the first link does not have a left router, the last link does not have a right router.

        The routing tables are filled with the entire list of links (no supernetting is used).

        The network is composed by IPv4 or Ipv6 routers depending on the type of the prefix address.

        Parameters:
        n - the number of routers
        bit_rate - link bit rate
        net_prefix - network prefix
        Returns:
        the new network

      • manhattanIpNetwork

        public static Network manhattanIpNetwork(int n,
                                         int m,
                                         long bit_rate,
                                         IpPrefix net_prefix)
        Creates a rectangular topology (Manhattan) with n*m routers and 2(n*m)+n+m links. The link addresses are automatically assigned starting from the given supernet prefix.

        No distinction is done between core and access links; all links are considered access links.

        The router addresses are assigned by giving host id 1 to the router on the south of the link, host id 2 to the router on the east, host id 3 to the router on the west, and host id 4 to the router on the north.

        The routing tables are filled with the entire list of links (no supernetting is used).

        The network is composed by IPv4 or Ipv6 routers depending on the type of the prefix address.

        Parameters:
        n - the number of rows
        m - the number of columns
        bit_rate - link bit rate
        net_prefix - network prefix
        Returns:
        the new network

      • treeIpCoreNetwork

        public static Network treeIpCoreNetwork(int degree,
                                        int height,
                                        long bit_rate,
                                        IpPrefix net_prefix)
        Creates a binary tree topology with (m^n)-1 routers and (m^(n+1))-2 links, where n is the tree height and m is the tree degree. Access networks are attached to the tree leaf routers: one access network for each leaf router.

        The network is composed by IPv4 or Ipv6 routers depending on the type of the prefix address.

        The network prefix is used to assign addresses to access networks only. Core links and core routers use a different network prefix (CORE_LOCAL_LINK_PREFIX4 for IPv4 and CORE_LOCAL_LINK_PREFIX6 for IPv6). In particular, all core links use the same prefix, while the router addresses are assigned as globally unique from that prefix. Each router has m+1 addresses (m is the degree of the tree).

        Parameters:
        net_prefix - network prefix
        height - the tree height (i.e. the number of tree levels)
        degree - the tree degree
        bit_rate - link bit rate
        Returns:
        the new network
